# API Security

Based on OWASP API Security Top 10 (2023).

## OWASP API Security Top 10

| # | Risk | Spring Boot Mitigation |
|---|------|----------------------|
| **API1** | Broken Object-Level Authorization (BOLA) | `@PreAuthorize` with ownership checks; never trust client-supplied IDs |
| **API2** | Broken Authentication | Spring Security `SecurityFilterChain`; JWT validation (issuer, audience, expiry) |
| **API3** | Broken Object Property Level Authorization | Response DTOs (records); never expose entity directly; `@JsonIgnore` for sensitive fields |
| **API4** | Unrestricted Resource Consumption | Rate limiting (Bucket4j / Resilience4j); request body size limits; pagination |
| **API5** | Broken Function-Level Authorization | Role-based method security; deny by default; audit admin endpoints |
| **API6** | Unrestricted Access to Sensitive Business Flows | CAPTCHA, device fingerprinting, rate limiting on critical flows (registration, checkout) |
| **API7** | Server-Side Request Forgery (SSRF) | Validate/allowlist URLs; no user-controlled URLs in server-side HTTP calls |
| **API8** | Security Misconfiguration | CORS restricted; Actuator secured; debug disabled in prod; security headers set |
| **API9** | Improper Inventory Management | OpenAPI spec as source of truth; deprecate old versions; no shadow/debug endpoints in prod |
| **API10** | Unsafe Consumption of APIs | Validate responses from third-party APIs; timeout + circuit breaker for external calls |

## Authentication
- Require authentication on all endpoints by default (`anyRequest().authenticated()`)
- OAuth2 / OIDC for external consumers via Spring Security OAuth2 Resource Server
- API keys for service-to-service communication (with rotation policy)
- JWT validation: verify signature, issuer (`iss`), audience (`aud`), expiration (`exp`)
- Use asymmetric keys (RS256/ES256), never symmetric secrets in code

```java
// Spring Security default: deny all, then allow specific paths
http.authorizeHttpRequests(auth -> auth
    .requestMatchers("/api/public/**").permitAll()
    .requestMatchers("/actuator/health").permitAll()
    .anyRequest().authenticated()
)
```

## Authorization
- **Object-level (BOLA prevention)**: Verify requester owns/can access the specific resource instance
- **Function-level**: Verify requester has the role/permission for the operation
- Never rely on client-supplied IDs for authorization decisions
- Use `@PreAuthorize` or `@Secured` for method-level checks

```java
@PreAuthorize("hasRole('USER') and @resourceSecurity.isOwner(#id, authentication)")
@GetMapping("/orders/{id}")
public OrderResponse getOrder(@PathVariable Long id) { /* ... */ }
```

## Rate Limiting
- Apply rate limits per client/API key using Bucket4j or Resilience4j
- Return `429 Too Many Requests` with `Retry-After` header
- Different limits for authenticated vs anonymous requests
- Use token bucket algorithm for burst tolerance
- Distributed rate limiting via Redis for multi-instance deployments

## Transport Security
- TLS 1.2+ for all API communication
- HSTS headers for browser-facing APIs
- Certificate pinning for mobile/embedded clients where feasible
- Spring Boot SSL bundles for TLS configuration

## CORS
- Configure explicitly for known origins only
- Never `Access-Control-Allow-Origin: *` in production
- Restrict allowed methods, headers, and credentials

```java
@Bean
public CorsConfigurationSource corsConfigurationSource() {
    var config = new CorsConfiguration();
    config.setAllowedOrigins(List.of("https://app.example.com"));
    config.setAllowedMethods(List.of("GET", "POST", "PUT", "DELETE"));
    config.setAllowedHeaders(List.of("Authorization", "Content-Type"));
    config.setAllowCredentials(true);
    var source = new UrlBasedCorsConfigurationSource();
    source.registerCorsConfiguration("/api/**", config);
    return source;
}
```

## Input Validation
- Validate content types: reject unexpected `Content-Type` headers
- Maximum request body size: `server.tomcat.max-http-form-post-size`, `spring.servlet.multipart.max-file-size`
- Jakarta Bean Validation on all request DTOs: `@Valid`, `@Size`, `@Pattern`, `@Positive`
- Reject requests with unexpected query parameters (strict binding)

## Response Security
- Remove server version headers (`server.server-header` in Spring Boot)
- `X-Content-Type-Options: nosniff`
- `Cache-Control: no-store` for sensitive data
- Never include sensitive data in URLs (query parameters are logged)
- Use RFC 9457 `ProblemDetail` for error responses -- no stack traces, no internal details

## SSRF Prevention (API7)
- Never pass user-controlled URLs to `RestClient`, `WebClient`, or `RestTemplate`
- Allowlist permitted external hosts
- Block internal/private IP ranges in outbound calls

## Logging and Monitoring
- Log all authentication/authorization events (success and failure)
- Detect and alert on anomalous patterns (brute force, credential stuffing, rate limit abuse)
- Include correlation IDs (MDC) for request tracing across services
- Never log secrets, tokens, or passwords
